d stones is 1 + 2 = 3 and is divisible by 3. Therefore, Bob loses and Alice wins the game.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: stones = [2]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: Alice will remove the only stone, and the sum of the values on the removed stones is 2. \nSince all the stones are removed and the sum of values is not divisible by 3, Bob wins the game.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: stones = [5,1,2,4,3]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: Bob will always win. One possible way for Bob to win is shown below:\n- Turn 1: Alice can remove the second stone with value 1. Sum of removed stones = 1.\n- Turn 2: Bob removes the fifth stone with value 3. Sum of removed stones = 1 + 3 = 4.\n- Turn 3: Alices removes the fourth stone with value 4. Sum of removed stones = 1 + 3 + 4 = 8.\n- Turn 4: Bob removes the third stone with value 2. Sum of removed stones = 1 + 3 + 4 + 2 = 10.\n- Turn 5: Alice removes the first stone with value 5. Sum of removed stones = 1 + 3 + 4 + 2 + 5 = 15.\nAlice loses the game because the sum of the removed stones (15) is divisible by 3. Bob wins the game.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= stones.length <= 105\n1 <= stones[i] <= 104\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def stoneGameIX(self, stones: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def stoneGameIX(self, stones: List[int]) -> bool:\n        # Count the number of stones with values % 3 == 0, 1, 2\n        count = [0, 0, 0]\n        for stone in stones:\n            count[stone % 3] += 1\n        \n        # If there are no stones with value % 3 == 0, the game reduces to a simple parity check\n        if count[0] % 2 == 0:\n            # If count[0] is even, Alice can always mirror Bob's moves\n            # Alice wins if there are both stones with value % 3 == 1 and value % 3 == 2\n            return count[1] > 0 and count[2] > 0\n        else:\n            # If count[0] is odd, Alice can only win if the difference between count[1] and count[2] is more than 2\n            # This is because she can force Bob into a losing position by using the odd count of 0s to balance the game\n            return abs(count[1] - count[2]) > 2\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently determines the winner based on the counts of stones with values congruent to 0, 1, and 2 modulo 3. The key insight is that the parity of the count of stones with value % 3 == 0 and the difference between the counts of stones with value % 3 == 1 and value % 3 == 2 determine the outcome of the game when both players play optimally.", "estimated_date": 1633219200000}